## Migration Analysis

Your code has **3 thread-termination patterns** that break on .NET 8:

| Location | Pattern | Problem on .NET 8 |
|----------|---------|-------------------|
| `Stop()` → `_thread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Stop()` → `_thread.Interrupt()` | Blocking call interruption | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9) |
| `RunLoop()` → `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | Blocking call that needs waking | Can't be interrupted without token |

### Race condition in original code (bug carried forward)

If multiple items are enqueued before `RunLoop` resets the event, only one is dequeued — the rest are lost. The migrated version fixes this too.

---

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var handles = new WaitHandle[] { _newEvent, _cts.Token.WaitHandle };

        while (!_cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny returns index of the signaled handle
            int signaled = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);

            // Index 1 = cancellation token was signaled → exit
            if (signaled == 1 || _cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
                break;

            // Drain all queued items (fixes original race condition)
            _newEvent.Reset();
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0)
                        break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();         // signals the token's WaitHandle
        _thread?.Join(5000);   // wait for graceful exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

### What changed and why

| Original | Migrated | Reason |
|----------|----------|--------|
| `while (true)` | `while (!_cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Cooperative exit check |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles)` | Wakes on **either** new item or cancellation |
| `_thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Signals the token's `WaitHandle`, unblocking `WaitAny` |
| `_thread.Abort()` | *(removed)* | Unnecessary — the loop exits cooperatively |
| No `Dispose` | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` and `WaitHandle` are disposable |
| Dequeue one item | Drain loop | Fixes lost-item race condition |

---

## Key Pitfalls

1. **`Thread.Abort` → `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — There is no equivalent. The thread *must* check the token and exit voluntarily.

2. **`WaitOne()` ignores cancellation** — You can't cancel a bare `WaitOne()`. You must use `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` as a second handle.

3. **Don't forget to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — It leaks timers and callbacks if not disposed.

4. **Cancellation is not immediate** — If `Handle(item)` takes 30 seconds, the loop won't check the token until it finishes. If you need faster cancellation, pass `_cts.Token` into `Handle()` and check it there.

5. **`Thread.Interrupt` is also obsolete** — Even though it still *works* on .NET 8, it's marked `SYSLIB0046` starting in .NET 9. Replace it now.
